7. Inverse probability weighting and meta analysis

2023-03-12

Back to content page

Learning objectives

  • Appreciate the use of inverse probability weighting
  • Apply inverse probability weighting for analysis of missing data
  • Perform meta analysis to obtain overall estimate of an intervention effect from multiple studies

1 Inverse probability weighting

Missing data

  • Potential reasons for missing data: dropout, incomplete response, censored
  • Types of missing data
    1. Missing completely at random (MCAR) missingness independent of all variables
      e.g.Accidental loss of data
    2. Missing at random (MAR) missingness dependent on observed variables
      e.g.Loss of contact of recovered patients
    3. Missing not at random (MNAR) missingness dependent on unobserved variables
      e.g.Patients with treatment failure less likely to respond
  • Methods to handle missing data
    • Valid for MCAR
      1. Complete case analysisOnly analyze cases with complete data
        • May lose substantial information
      2. Nearest neighbour imputationImpute missing value from most similar subject
      3. Mean imputationImpute missing values by the mean of the variable
        • Reduces variation in the data
        • May not maintain associations between variables
    • Valid for MAR
      1. Regression imputationPredict missing value from regression models (linear regression or other GLM)
      2. Multiple imputation (will be covered in CMED6040)Single imputation treats imputed values as actual responses
        • Multiple imputation accounts for variability/uncertainty in the imputed data
      3. Inverse probability weightingEstimate the probability of response based on some external knowledge
        • Weight the observed data using the inverse probability

Example: BMI

  • Suppose we want to estimate the mean BMI in the population
  • Suppose we have a target population where
    • Male has a uniformly distributed BMI from 25 to 40 kg/m2
    • Female has a uniformly distributed BMI from 15 to 30 kg/m2
    • We randomly recruited a sample of 500 persons for each sex
    • The true mean BMI is (40+25+15+30)/4 = 27.5 kg/m2
    • From previous experience, 80% of the female will not report their BMI, but all male are willing to report their BMI => Missing at random
  • How should we estimate the mean BMI based on the observed sample?

1.1 Simulate dataset

###Simulate dataset with missing value
set.seed(123) #unify our results
n=500
bmi.m <- runif(n, 25, 40) #M unif distribution
bmi.f <- runif(n, 15, 30) #F unif distribution
bmi.full <- cbind(bmi.m, bmi.f) ##dataset without missing value
pi <- rep(c(1, 0.2), each=n) #NOTE the use of "each"; prob of observed for M and F
obs <- rbinom(2*n, 1, pi) 
bmi.obs <- bmi.full[obs==1] ##dataset with missing value

###Visualize the dataset
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
hist(bmi.obs, breaks=c(15,20,25,30,35,40))
hist(bmi.full, breaks=c(15,20,25,30,35,40))
#The observed data has a very different BMI distribution due to missing response from female

1.2 Inverse probability weighting

  • Apply a weighting which is the inverse of the probability of being observed
    E.g. A sample has a probability of 20% being observed => weight = 1/20% = 5
    • Specify as a function of X (i.e.(X, )) (X is other predictor like age of sex)

mean(bmi.obs) #This estimate (complete case analysis) is biased due to missing value

pi.obs <- pi[obs==1] #The probability of being observed for each data
sum(bmi.obs/pi.obs)/(2*n) #Apply weighting and calculate the mean
##27.1 is closer to true mean BMI than 30.8
## [1] 30.84461
## [1] 27.05842

1.3 Propensity score (inverse probability) weighting

Example: MI

Population: 400 men aged 40-70 admitted to hospital with suspected myocardial infarction

mi <- read.csv("Folder/examplemi.csv")
#Outcome variable: 30-day mortality
#Exposure/treatment: newer clot-busting drug vs standard therapy
##Confounders: age, pre-existing risk factor level (0-5, 5: highest risk),
#admission severity score (0-10, 10: most severe)
ps.model <- glm(trt~age+risk+severity, data=mi, family=binomial)
mi$ps <- predict(ps.model, type="response")

Counterfactuals: What would have happened if the patient received a different treatment (contrary to observed treatment taken)?

  • Propensity score p as the probability of being observed receiving newer treatment
  • 1-p as the probability of being observed receiving standard therapy

with(mi, (sum(death[trt==1]/ps[trt==1]) - sum(death[trt==0]/(1-ps)[trt==0]))/400)
with(mi, sum(death/ps*(trt==1) - death/(1-ps)*(trt==0)))/nrow(mi)  
#NOTE: "*(trt==1)" = those treatment not equal to 1 will become 0
##Estimated effect for clot-busting therapy: -0.065 (-0.163, 0.033)
## [1] -0.06516998
## [1] -0.06516998

2 Meta analysis

Example: e-cigarrette
  • Aim: assess the association between e-cigarette use and cigarette smoking cessation among adult smokers interested in quitting smoking
  • 7 previous studies in 2013-2015. Reported adjusted ORs and their 95% CI
  • Data: extracted from Kalkhoran et al., Lancet Respir Med, 2016
ecig <- read.csv("Folder/exampleecig.csv") #OR.lb and OR.ub = lower and upper bound

# Convert OR to log OR (so that it's normal)
ecig$logOR <- log(ecig$OR)
# Derive the standard error for log OR from the 95% CI
ecig$se.logOR <- (log(ecig$OR.ub)-log(ecig$OR.lb))/(2*1.96)

2.1 Heterogeneity and models

  1. Clinical diversityVariability in participants, interventions and outcomes
    • E.g. different age groups
  2. Methodological diversityVariability in study design and risk of bias
    • E.g. RCT vs cohort study
  3. Statistical heterogeneityVariability in the intervention effects across studies
    • Violate the assumption for fixed effects model
    • Random effects model allows the true effect to be different across studies

Clinical / methodological diversity should be addressed in the systematic review (i.e.write it down in summary table (main text or appendix). Focus on statistical heterogeneity in the following slides.

  • Metrics to measure heterogeneity
    1. Cochrans Q test
      \(Q = \sum_{i}w_{i}(Y_{i}-\hat{\theta})^{2}\sim X^{2}\)
      • H0: no heterogeneity among studies (accept or reject based on p-val)
      • Q depends on no. of studies
    2. Higgins I2
      \(I^2 = (Q df)/Q \times 100\)
      • df = no. of studies - 1
      • Higher I2 = higher heterogeneity
      • Rule of thumb: low: 0-30%, moderate: 30-60%, substantial: 50-90%
  • 2 models
    1. Fixed effects model
      Assuming true effect of intervention is the same across studies
    2. Random effects model
      Assuming the true intervention effect of each study comes from a larger population (subset of a larger population)
Fixed effect model

Random effect model

A. Fixed effects model

  • rma(yi, vi, sei, data, method=REML, slab ) (in package: metafor)
    • yi outcome measures or effect size
    • vi sei corresponding sampling variance or standard error (either one)
    • data specifies the data frame
    • method FE for fixed effects model, REML for random effects model (default)
    • slab study label
## Carry out meta analysis using fixed effects model
require(metafor)
ecig.fe <- rma(yi=logOR, sei=se.logOR, slab=study, method="FE", data=ecig)
with(ecig.fe, exp(c(b, ci.lb, ci.ub))) #estimate, lower, upper bound
#The overall estimate is 0.77 (95% CI = 0.69-0.87)

## Test for heterogeniety 
summary(ecig.fe) #Q p-val <0.05 --> reject no heterogeneity 
Q <- ecig.fe$QE
I2 <- (Q-(ecig.fe$k-1))/Q * 100 #I^2 = 88% --> heterogeneity
I2

B. Random effects model

## Carry out meta analysis using random effects model
ecig.re <- rma(yi=logOR, sei=se.logOR, slab=study, data=ecig)
with(ecig.re, exp(c(b, ci.lb, ci.ub)))
## [1] 0.8589488 0.5961948 1.2375035
#The overall estimate is 0.86 (95% CI = 0.60-1.24)
#Include uncertainty in random effect model --> wider CI compared to FE

2.2 Forest plot

  • forest(x, showweights=FALSE, transf, refline=0, order, ) (in package: metafor)
    • x an rma object obtained by FE/RE model
    • showweights TRUE (default) to show the weighting for each study
    • transf=exp to take exponential transformation for the outcome measure
    • refline specifies the reference line (0/1 depending on outcome measure)
    • order specifies order in effect size: obs; sampling variance: prec
## Forest plot
par(mfrow=c(1,1))
forest(ecig.re, transf=exp, refline=1)

# No evidence that e-cigarette use is helpful to smoking cessation
# But large heterogeneity (some study less than 1, some greater than 1)

2.3 Funnel plot

Symmetrical funnel plot

  • A symmetric inverted funnel shape is expected if studies are of good methodological quality and no reporting bias exists
    • Larger studies likely to be near the top and closer to center line (high precision, low SE)
    • Less useful for small no. of studies
  • Asymmetry may arise from multiple reasons:
    1. Reporting biases
    2. Poor methodological quality
    3. True heterogeneity
    4. Due to Chance
  • Scatter plot of the effect estimates (X) versus precision (Y)
    • Vertical dotted line: overall estimate; diagonal: 95% CI
  • funnel(x, yaxis=sei, atransf, refline) (in package: metafor)
    • x an rma object
    • yaxis specifies what is shown on the y-axis. sei for standard error, vi for variance, ni for sample size
    • atransf=exp to take exponential transformation for x-axis (outcome measure)
    • refline specifies the reference line
## Funnel plot
funnel(ecig.re, atransf=exp)

#Not obvious asymmetry
#Large heterogeneity (can see dots around)

Test of asymmetry in the funnel plot

  • Eggers test
    • regtest() in package metafor
    • Low power with small number of studies (e.g.n < 10)
  • Other tests: Beggs test, Harbords test
  • Specify the test before analysis
regtest(ecig.re)
## 
## Regression Test for Funnel Plot Asymmetry
## 
## Model:     mixed-effects meta-regression model
## Predictor: standard error
## 
## Test for Funnel Plot Asymmetry: z = 0.7469, p = 0.4552
## Limit Estimate (as sei -> 0):   b = -0.5339 (CI: -1.6063, 0.5385)
#p-val= 0.4552 => no strong evidence of asymmetry (but bear in mind it's **small sample size**)

Remarks

  • rma in R can also handle some type of original data (e.g.2 x 2 table frequencies, observed no. of outcomes, etc)
    • All can be transformed into effect size and corresponding variances (to fulfill normal assumptions(?))
  • Higher heterogeneity => do Meta-regression
    • Allow for potential moderator on the study effect size
    • R: can be specified in the mod option in rma() function (can put predictors/variable inside to see which one is causing heterogeneity)
  • In the presence of reporting bias => Trim and fill (see tutorial 3)
    • Estimate the overall effect by filling the missing studies
    • As a sensitivity analysis

Summary

  • To obtain an overall estimates of an intervention from studies with similar interventions and outcomes
  • Give higher weighting to studies with higher precision
  • Need to assess study heterogeneity
  • Refer to PRISMA / MOOSE for guidelines
